;; kUML MCP script-sandbox — macOS OS-native isolation profile (Welle 4).
;;
;; Apple Sandbox Profile Language ("Seatbelt"). Applied to every script-worker
;; child JVM (dev.kuml.core.script.ScriptWorkerMain) via:
;;
;;     sandbox-exec -D WORKDIR=<per-worker temp dir> \
;;                  -D USERHOME=<user home> \
;;                  -f kuml-worker.macos.sb \
;;                  <java> ... dev.kuml.core.script.ScriptWorkerMain
;;
;; Threat model (see the MCP-Skript-Sandbox architecture note): an untrusted
;; script may attempt to (a) exfiltrate files (~/.ssh, ~/.aws, credentials),
;; (b) open a network connection to exfiltrate data or pivot, (c) drop a
;; persistence artefact on disk. Even if the regex denylist (layer 1) and the
;; process/heap/timeout containment (Wellen 2-3) are all bypassed, this OS layer
;; must still make those three goals impossible.
;;
;; Security posture:
;;   * DENY BY DEFAULT — nothing is permitted unless explicitly allowed below.
;;   * NETWORK: fully denied. Blocks both DNS-based and direct-IP connections,
;;     inbound and outbound (empirically verified: UnknownHostException on
;;     name resolution, SocketException on raw-IP connect).
;;   * FILE WRITE: denied everywhere EXCEPT the per-worker temp WORKDIR (which
;;     the parent creates and destroys) plus the harmless character devices.
;;     A write to $HOME (e.g. trojanising ~/.zshrc, dropping a launchd plist)
;;     fails with "Operation not permitted" at the kernel, not merely the JVM.
;;   * FILE READ: broadly allowed (the embedded Kotlin compiler + jlink runtime
;;     read from dozens of scattered classpath/JDK locations, so an exact
;;     per-jar allowlist would be extremely brittle across dependency bumps and
;;     jlink-layout changes). Broad read is acceptable as a FIRST OS layer
;;     because the high-value attack goals — exfiltration and network pivot —
;;     both require WRITE or NETWORK, both of which are denied. As
;;     defence-in-depth the most sensitive secret directories are additionally
;;     read-denied below (later rules override the earlier broad allow in SBPL).
;;   * PROCESS: the worker's own `java` may fork threads/helper processes it
;;     needs to boot, but every such child inherits THIS sandbox (there is no
;;     `(with no-sandbox)` escape hatch), so a script cannot exec an unconfined
;;     subprocess. Combined with the network + write denies, an exec'd child is
;;     itself caged.
;;
;; NB on `sandbox-exec`: officially deprecated by Apple but still present and
;; heavily used by Apple's own components. It is ORTHOGONAL to AMFI / Library
;; Validation: `sandbox-exec` itself carries no hardened-runtime / LV codesign
;; flag, so wrapping an ad-hoc-signed bundled JRE in it does NOT trigger the
;; separate AMFI adhoc-dylib rejection (empirically verified — see the AMFI note
;; and the Welle-4 daily log). The two mechanisms do not interact.

(version 1)

;; ── Baseline: refuse everything not explicitly granted ────────────────────
(deny default)

;; ── Process lifecycle the JVM needs to boot and run ───────────────────────
;; No (with no-sandbox): every child stays inside this profile.
(allow process-fork)
(allow process-exec)
(allow signal (target self))

;; ── System introspection the JVM performs at startup ──────────────────────
(allow sysctl-read)
(allow mach-lookup)

;; ── File reads: broad (see rationale above) ───────────────────────────────
(allow file-read*)
(allow file-read-metadata)

;; ── File writes: ONLY the per-worker temp workdir + harmless devices ──────
(allow file-write* (subpath (param "WORKDIR")))
(allow file-write-data
  (literal "/dev/null")
  (literal "/dev/random")
  (literal "/dev/urandom")
  (literal "/dev/zero"))

;; ── Network: fully denied ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
(deny network*)

;; ── Defence-in-depth read-denies on the highest-value secret stores ───────
;; These override the broad (allow file-read*) above (last-match-wins in SBPL),
;; so even a read attempt on these paths fails at the kernel.
(deny file-read* (subpath (string-append (param "USERHOME") "/.ssh")))
(deny file-read* (subpath (string-append (param "USERHOME") "/.aws")))
(deny file-read* (subpath (string-append (param "USERHOME") "/.gnupg")))
(deny file-read* (subpath (string-append (param "USERHOME") "/.config/gcloud")))
(deny file-read* (subpath (string-append (param "USERHOME") "/Library/Keychains")))
